post_text: With the help of some of last year's 6th grade students, Dr. Jahnke and Mrs. Messenger have assembled over 400 Scott Success Sacks for their students. Each Scott Success Sack includes school supplies needed for students to begin their virtual learning on Monday, August 31st. Parents should sign up for a time to pick up their child's Success Sack this week at Scott 6th Grade Center. The link to sign up will be included in this week's Monday Morning Message. #casdbacktoschool

City of Coatesville Police Department
August 3 at 2:16 PM ¬∑

While on patrol today, we had the pleasure of 'catching' Donnelle in the act of doing something right. She was observed contributing to her community by making certain that the storm drains were clear since a storm is in the forecast. We learned from several eyewitnesses that she is frequently seen in the area cleaning up and helping others. Today, her conduct had consequences...Thanks to partnerships with David's Drive and Chester County Safe Kids Coalition, she left the police station with a new bike and safety helmet. Well done, Donnelle...We appreciate your hard work and sense of care. We hope that you enjoy your new ride and continue to strive to make a difference.
#CPDcares #communitypolicing #ThisisCoatesville #coatesvillepride #copsandkids

City of Coatesville Police Department
July 29 at 2:54 PM ¬∑

Today, we had the pleasure of meeting Nevaeh and DeAmoni. They were 'caught' doing something right and it had consequences. Since they brought smiles to our faces (not that you can see) and were positively contributing to our community, we decided to bring smiles to their faces (not that you can see). Thanks to partnerships with David's Drive 831 and Safe Kids Chester County, we were able to set them up with new bikes and safety helmets. Well done, ladies. Your pleasant demeanor, caring attitude and hard work paid off today. Keep it up...Those traits will certainly continue to have positive consequences in the future.
#CPDcares #communitypolicing #copsandkids #ThisisCoatesville

To ensure the Coatesville Area School District continues to make fiscally sound decisions, the transportation department is gathering information to assist with developing bus schedules. The goal is to decrease transportation costs by reducing the number of buses needed to transport students living within school district boundaries.

This is a challenging task that requires accurate information. To ensure we have accurate transportation information, please use the link below to assist us with developing our transportation plan for the 2020-2021 school year.

https://forms.gle/52MebqQvDw1xknRT6

After you access the link please list your child‚Äôs name, grade, and school and select one of the transportation options listed below.

Please complete the link for each child in your home that is of school age. Your feedback is extremely important and will provide the CASD transportation department with accurate information about your child‚Äôs transportation needs.

Earlier this year before everything changed, the seniors of the Coatesville Area String Orchestra chose "We're All In This Together" to be their senior song. Not the one that we're all used to from the last movie but the graduation version from the third movie! It couldn't be more fitting for both the seniors this year and with everything else that has occurred. The seniors worked hard independently to practice and record themselves playing and we couldn't be more proud of the outcome. Congratulations to the graduating class of 2020! May your futures shine as bright as you shine now! #Classof2020 #ThisisCoatesville üíïüé∂

post_text:
This a very exciting week for East Fallowfield and the Coatesville Area School District. As many of you may have already heard, our very own kindergarten teacher, Mrs. Heather McBall was nominated for the Citadel Heart of Learning Award. She went on to win and became the representative for the entire Coatesville Area School District! She is now in the running for the final three grand prizes. Typically, this honor is celebrated with a beautiful banquet. However, with the current circumstances, Citadel will be broadcasting live from Facebook. It would be wonderful to have our East Fallowfield and Coatesville families on and supporting Mrs. McBall.

The link to follow the event for the Citadel Heart of Learning Award virtual banquet tomorrow, Tuesday, May 19th is now live: https://www.facebook.com/CitadelBanking/posts/3617066451653334.

Thank you to everyone who sent in pictures and videos. We were able to compile them into one video of love and support for Mrs. McBall. We hope you enjoy! https://youtu.be/gFfX3oYm2vg

post_text: Students in Miss Kriston's Kindergarten class at East Fallowfield had a very successful math lesson today called Bead Combinations! They had to make a beaded bracelet with either 7, 8, 9, or 10 beads, and then had to break their beads into combinations and record the addition problem. For example, if they put 10 beads on their string they could put 8 beads on one side and 2 beads on the other side of the bracelet and then write 8+2=10. They had a blast showing off their work today. üíï #KindergartenKiddos #VirtualLearning #QuarantineActivities #ThisisCoatesville

post_text: Wyatt, a Kindergarten Kiddo from East Fallowfield, loves connecting with his teacher, Miss Kriston. Wyatt's mom sent Miss Kriston these pictures and said he will only listen if he is watching a video of her teaching a lesson...then he will sit and listen and work so hard!! These videos are saving her life she said! It is the little things, that seem to be going a long way for students and their families, such as hearing their teachers' voices or seeing their faces that is getting students through all this! Students are really missing their teachers right now, and we know the teachers are missing their students. But we are grateful that under these circumstances, we are still able to connect. üíï

Please give it up for seniors Patrick McManamon and Autumn Barnard for their hard work putting these photos together for their classmates! We will be adding more senior photos as we get them, but in the meantime, please help us congratulate all of these wonderful students. Students, we wish you all well in your future endeavors, and remember: once a raider, always a raider! #ThisisCoatesville #Classof2020 #NobleRedandBlack

Many taxpayers have expressed interest in receiving district communications emails. If you would like to keep up to date with communications that the District sends out to our families and staff members, you can sign up at this link. Please note, if you already have a student enrolled in the district, you DO NOT need to sign up again. This list will be for taxpayers within the Coatesville Area School District who do not have any children currently enrolled in the District (retirees, business owners, etc.)

Please enter your contact information by clicking on this link: https://forms.gle/E5qeqjmWEZjxi2zv8

post_text:
The technology department has added more dates and times for Chromebook pickup. Will are offering pickups on April 13th, 14th, 16th and 17th, with time slots from 9:00 am to 3:00 pm. Appointments will be set up by date and time only, no unscheduled walk-ins will be permitted. One person will be permitted to pickup/drop off devices during the scheduled Date/Time at our Coatesville Area School district office, 3030 C.G. Zinn Road, Thorndale. If returning a broken device, please place it in the box marked 'Returns'. Please fill out one form for each device. If you have additional questions about Chromebook pickup/drop off, please contact IThelpdesk@casdschools.org. Thank you!

Link to schedule a Chromebook appointment: https://forms.gle/PkRcTng5yrj2TYHM8

post_text:
Hi Students and Families,
I wanted you to know that my whole family is thinking of you on School Spirit Day! My son David who lives with my husband Kevin and I in Coatesville, my son Ryan from Philly with his girlfriend Lauren, my daughter Kara and her husband Patrick in Kensington, Maryland and my daughter Kailin and her husband Scott in Cincinnati, Ohio all are dressed in red and black for our School Spirit Day. Hi East Fallowfield and Coatesville families!! Happy belated St. Patty's Day ‚òò from Mrs. Billman. I miss teaching you Science and doing fun activities, so I am doing them with my children. Here are some great websites for you and your family to explore and enjoy STEM at home!
‚Ä¢ MAD SCIENCE -https://www.madsciencepromo.com/-
‚Ä¢ MYSTERY DOUG- https://mysterydoug.com/-
‚Ä¢ Brain Pop jr- https://jr.brainpop.com/- user name
casd1234 password- casd1234

If you would like more activities or want to share what you are doing at home, you can email me at Billmanj@casdschools.org. I would love to see what you are doing.

Here are some pictures of my kids doing some STEM projects at home. Stay safe and I hope you find LUCK in the next couple of weeks. I can't wait to see you!

‚òò Mrs. Billman ‚òò

Starting March 17th to the 27 th 2020 Iccara Pizza is starting from 11AM to 2PM free lunch for our Coatesville students K-12! The options are a slice of pizza with apple juice or orange juice or spaghetti with sauce and a apple juice or orange juice. We want to help our community as much as we can during this time. This free lunch will be pick-up only!

shared_text:
City of Coatesville Police Department
March 16 at 8:25 AM ¬∑

As our followers are fully aware, our policing strategy strongly encourages officers to engage with the public as often as possible. Being part of community activities and forging constructive relationships is important to our organization and the community we serve. With COVID-19 mandates and recommended safe practices in policing, you may notice less engagement and we may be handling more calls for service by phone. We've asked officers to maintain social distance when possible. We ask the public to do the same and be mindful of everyone's safety during this challenging time.
#CPDcares #CommunityPolicing

post_text: Thank you Coatesville Area Senior Center this is wonderful! üíï
shared_text:
Coatesville Area Senior Center
March 16 at 10:05 AM ¬∑

Coatesville Area Senior Center will offer pre-packaged meals tomorrow for those persons 60 and older who need a meal. Meals will be served at the side door in our parking lot starting at 12-noon and will be available until 1:30PM.

If you are someone 60 or older, or you know someone 60 or older who needs a meal delivered, please call our office at 610-383-6900 and leave their name and phone number so we can reach out to them.

PLEASE NOTE: the Coatesville Area Senior Center remains CLOSED. You will not be permitted to enter the building. A member of the CASC team will bring a meal to you.

Thank you for your patience and understanding and thank you for helping us to SPREAD THE WORD!

post_text: Update on the States Competition for the Raiderbots. The Raiderbots finished 16th out of 24 teams in the Alleghany division. Divisions are random and do not reflect geographic location. We won 2 out of 5 matches. After a strong start to the day, we faced some technical issues with the autonomous part of our code (that worked in many practice runs) leading us to lose two matches by less than 10 points. The Raiderbots rallied after each loss and went right to work finding solutions. Unfortunately, we were not picked for a finalist alliance. On a positive note, Out of the Box, the community team that operates out of the 11/12 that provides us with support did move on to worlds in Detroit. We are so proud of the Raiderbots and all they have accomplished! ‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§ #CoatesvillePride #ThisisCoatesville

post_text:
Today, rumors have been spreading of a Corona Virus case at the Coatesville VA Medical Center. These rumors are FALSE. Unfortunately, these rumors began during a social studies class in which ‚Äúfake news‚Äù was being discussed. There is a realistic-looking graphic being shared which appears to show a screen shot of a TV news broadcast with ‚Äúbreaking news‚Äù announcing the virus.

We apologize for any concern this may have caused, and for any misjudgment on the part of any faculty member in exploring this topic with our students.

We confirmed with the Chester County Health Department and the VA Medical Center that this is purely a rumor and Corona Virus has not been detected at the hospital or anywhere in our county.

post_text: We are extremely pleased to inform you that on Saturday, February 1st, the Raiderbots competed in the FTC Southeastern Pennsylvania Qualifier held at Oxford Area High School. The competition hosted 30 teams across the country (one team even came as far as Ohio State). The Raiderbots won 4 of 5 qualifying matches, we made it the semi-finals and earned the title of 4th place captain alliance. While the Raiderbots found a good fight, we were defeated by less than 10 points, and earned 7th place out of the 30 teams that we competed against, the top 5 teams advanced to State Companionship (so we just missed). We are so proud of this team! #CoatesvillePride #ThisisCoatesville ‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§

post_text:
On December 12th, the Coatesville Area Senior High School Academic Team traveled to Malvern Prep to take on Conestoga High School and Malvern Prep in the third match of the school year. The Varsity and Junior Varsity teams finished ahead of Malvern Prep, placing second in their respective competitions.

In the Team's fourth match of the school year, held January 10th at the Chester County Intermediate Unit, the Varsity team placed third to Devon Prep and Avon Grove Charter. The Junior Varsity Team placed second, well ahead of Avon Grove Charter and one question behind Devon Prep, for its best point performance of the season.

The Academic Team's competition season wraps up at the end of February with the Chester County Intermediate Unit's Semi-Final Playoff Match. Good luck to this outstanding group of students. #CoatesvillePride ‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§

Friends of Reeceville PTA
January 13 at 4:48 PM ¬∑

We ‚ù§Ô∏è seeing Reeceville students in action!

The 5th grade just finished their second Project Lead the
Way module, called "Robotics & Automation." Students built and investigated test beds with motors, color sensors, bumper switches, and touch LEDs. They worked in groups to research and present information on different types of robots (industrial, consumer, medical, military & security, exoskeletons, and telepresence), then built and modified robots to solve a real-world problem: locating & removing radioactive uranium fuel from the Fukushima nuclear disaster site in Japan.

Thank you to our awesome STEM/Science teacher Mrs. Canning, and way to go, Reeceville fifth graders!

Coatesville Area School District

shared_text:
Coatesville Swimming & Diving
January 3 at 11:12 PM ¬∑

The girls team beat WC East tonight 102-78. Our girls won every individual swimming event in the meet.
Lauren Wolstenholme won the 200 & 500 free. Mackenzie Yosko won the 200 IM & 100 back. Kayla Bock won the 50 & 100 free. Jordyn DiCamillo won the 100 fly & 100 breast. Sarah McManamon took second in diving.
The 200 Medley Relay team of Mackenzie Yosko, Melanie Bohm, Jordyn DiCamillo, and Francesca Sciarretta took first. And the 200 Free Relay team of Jordyn DiCamillo, Olivia Hillman, Lauren Wolstenholme, and Kayla Bock placed first.
Special shout out to Kayla Bock for achieving an automatic District qualifying time of 25.19 in the 50 free.
The girls team is now undefeated at 3-0. Congratulations ladies!!‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§

post_text:
High school science teachers and coaches of our district robotics team, Octavia Warren-Ward and Brian Ulkloss, invite all students in grades 4 through 8 to come out and see what robotics is all about.
Our district robotics team, Raiderbots, will be hosting a fundraiser "Discover Robotics Workshop". The workshop will be held on Saturday, December 14, 2019 from 10am until 3pm at the Coatesville Area Senior High School (Room 145). Lunch will be provided to participants. It could be a great opportunity for parents to get some December shopping done too! The registration website is found below.

In addition to introducing students to the world of robotics, this workshop is also a fundraiser to help team Raiderbots raise money needed to build their competition robot this year. If you have any questions, please contact Octavia Warren-Ward at warrenwardo@casdschools.org or Brian Ulkloss at ulklossb@casdschools.org.

Registration link: https://coatesvillearea.revtrak.net/High-School-9/hs-raiderbots-fundraiser/

post_text: In response to accusations that there are no police officers at the high school, we can assure you that they are. Two of the Coatesville Area School District Police officers were on duty all day yesterday and today at the high school. Six police officers from Caln Police Department, Coatesville Police Department, and the West Caln Police Department were at the high school during arrival yesterday. They rotated on the main campus throughout the day, and came back for dismissal time. This morning, a combination of eleven officers were there for arrival, and they have been rotating in and out of the buildings, as well as visiting other schools in the district to make sure our schools are safe, and that we remain vigilant throughout the district. Two of our armed Coatesville School District Police Officers have remained in the building today. We are following the direction for security protocols from the police forces that support our district. Our students and staff safety remains our top priority.

The Crime Victims' Center of Chester County, Inc.
August 28, 2019 at 9:09 AM ¬∑

Did you know that over ** 450 ** teachers and staff in the Coatesville Area School District participated in the Stewards of Children training before school started? This training teaches adults how to prevent, recognize and react responsibly to childhood sexual abuse.

Thank you to all the participants for a great session and best wishes for a great academic year!
